# Lim Fang Yi, Jessica _v_ Fang Jianshuo  

### \[2022\] SGMC 30

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">Magistrate Court Suit No 4824 of 2019 (Assessment of Damages No 4 of 2021)</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">25 May 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">Magistrates Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Lewis Tan</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Ravendra Krishnasamy (Vision Law LLC) for the plaintiff; Foo Yuk Lin (Goodwins Law Corporation) for the defendant.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Lim Fang Yi, Jessica — Fang Jianshuo</td></tr></tbody></table>

Damages – Assessment

25 May 2022 - Judgment reserved.

### Deputy Registrar Lewis Tan:

## Introduction

1       A seemingly minor reversing collision caused little visible damage to the Plaintiff’s vehicle, and the Plaintiff continued driving her car until two months later, when she sent it for repairs. The repairer, on a surveyor’s recommendation, proceeded to replace many parts of the Plaintiff’s vehicle, including her front bumper, front headlight, as well as her sports wheel and tyre, and the eventual repair bill was close to $10,000.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) This hefty bill was strenuously disputed by the Defendant, who submitted that the repair costs ought to be about $1,000 only.[^2]

## Facts

2       On the morning of 2 August 2018, the Defendant was reversing his car into a carpark lot that was adjacent to the Plaintiff’s parked Mercedes car. While reversing, the Defendant’s car collided with the Plaintiff’s stationary vehicle, and this caused the Plaintiff, who was then seated in her car, to hear a “thud” as the side of the Defendant’s vehicle hit the “front right bumper of \[her\] car”.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3)

3       The mild collision caused some scratches on the front right-hand side of the Plaintiff’s car. The Plaintiff’s car was otherwise driveable, and repair works were only done in early October 2018, about two months after the accident.[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) Such repair works were performed by Fastech Auto Pte Ltd (“the Repairer”), which quoted the Plaintiff about $10,000 for the repair works.[^5] This sum was revised downwards to $9,100 (before 7% Goods and Services Tax (“GST”)) after a survey conducted by M/s Constant Appraiser Services (“the Surveyor”).[^6] In addition to the repair costs, arrangements were made for the Plaintiff to receive a replacement vehicle from Dynamic Car Rental (“the Car Rental Company”), a company affiliated with the Repairer, during the period of repair.

4       Based on the invoices issued by the Repairer and the Car Rental Company, the Plaintiff claims $11,357 against the Defendant, this being the sum total of the cost of repair ($9,737), the rental fees ($1,260) and for her loss of use for the pre-repair survey ($360). The bulk of the repair costs were allegedly incurred due to damage to the front right headlight, the front bumper and to the front right wheel of the Plaintiff’s car.[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7) However, despite the invoices issued, no payment has been made by the Plaintiff to the Repairer or the Car Rental Company to date.[^8]

5       The single joint expert, Mr Paul Thanabal (“SJE”), recommended that several aspects of the repair works done were “not necessary”, and the lump sum repair costs recommended by the SJE was $6,750 before GST.[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9) Before me, the representative of the Repairer, Mr Tang Jun Zhong (“Mr Tang”), testified that this reduced sum proposed by the SJE was acceptable.[^10]

6       In this judgment, I assess the heads of claim made by the Plaintiff in the same order as the Repairer and the SJE.[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11)

## Cost of repair

### Front bumper

7       First, $1,831.60 is quoted for the front bumper replacement. The Defendant concedes that the slight force could cause a crack to the clip part of the front bumper, and so “a replacement would be fair”.[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12) This is consistent with the SJE’s evidence, who explained that merely repairing the damaged bumper by puttying and applying primer and a fresh coat of paint would cause the plastic bumper to stretch as heat would have to be applied. This would then result in the plastic losing its sovereignty.[^13]

8       However, the Defendant submits that the price of $1,831.60 is “not real nor justified”, as the price of a replacement part could be much cheaper. Given the age of the car at the time of the accident, it is submitted that a notional diminution of value is warranted, and that only 30% of the list price (ie, $608.34) should be awarded. No authority is cited for this proposition. Furthermore, the issue of a notional discount was not put to the witnesses, including the SJE, and no rational basis is provided for the 30% figure.

9       Fundamentally, tortious damages seek to place the innocent party in the position he/she would have been in but for the tort (_Livingstone v The Rawyards Coal Company_ \[1880\] 5 App Cas 25 at 39). This applies equally to claims for property damage, so that where a vehicle is damaged by the negligence of another, the loss suffered by the victim is the diminution in value of the vehicle. If the vehicle can be economically repaired, “the practical way that the courts have calculated the diminution in value is to ask how much would be the reasonable cost of repair so as to put the \[vehicle\] back in the state it was in before it was damaged”: _Coles v Hetherton_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 1 WLR 160</span> at \[27\].

10     Here, the SJE’s evidence is that the bumper replacement was _necessary_, and there is no contradictory evidence in this regard. In fact, the Defendant accepts that such replacement would have been fair. In my judgment, it was entirely reasonable for the Plaintiff to have obtained a new bumper rather than one that was of equivalent age to her original damaged bumper as searching for such a like-for-like replacement would likely have been futile, and the search could also have increased the cost of the repair. Additionally, given that the Plaintiff would not have had to replace her bumper but for the Defendant’s negligence, the Plaintiff should be compensated for the full cost of the replacement bumper. To apply a notional discount as submitted by the Defendant would be to require the Plaintiff to bear part of the replacement cost, such that she would worse off, rather than put in the same position that she was in (_ie_, with a front bumper that did not require replacement) before the accident. Accordingly, she is entitled to the cost of the bumper replacement, which has been quoted at $1,831.60, and which figure the SJE has accepted.

11     In addition to the front bumper, the SJE gave uncontradicted evidence that the ancillary aspects of the front bumper, namely the front bumper retainer and the front bumper top seal, had to be replaced along with the front bumper.[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14) Flowing from my finding that the front bumper had to be replaced because of the accident, the claims for these ancillary aspects (being $55 + $141.20) are also allowed.

### Front bumper sensor

12     Turning then to the front bumper sensor, the Defendant submits that “\[t\]here is no evidence that this item was … spoilt”, and the Plaintiff in fact drove the car until October 2018 and did not complain of a spoilt sensor.

13     However, the SJE had stated on the stand that the sensor replaced was the “angle sensor”, which is one of four sensors on the front bumper. Based on the point of contact, and giving the benefit of the doubt, the SJE, who did not physically survey the Plaintiff’s vehicle, recommended that this head of claim be allowed.[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15) It should also be noted that this head of claim had already been adjusted downwards by the Surveyor, who indicated that only one of two sensors cited by the Repairer was malfunctioned.[^16] Given the SJE’s and Surveyor’s uncontradicted findings, I accept that one front bumper sensor was damaged due to the collision, and this head of claim is allowed at $313.75.

### Front bumper frame pad

14     The Plaintiff claims a further $441.50 for the crack to her front bumper frame pad. In response, the Defendant refers to several photographs that suggest that there was no such crack to the bumper.

15     These are material points that ought to have been raised to the SJE so that he could have had a chance to respond and to give the necessary evidence in this respect: _Browne v Dunn_ (1893) 6 R 67. Despite this, none of the photographs that the Defendant now refers to in its submissions were shown to the SJE _in the context of the front bumper frame pad_, and the only questions pertaining to this part were as follows:[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17)

No attempts were made to contradict this, whether by reference to other photographs or otherwise, nor did the counsel attempt to challenge the SJE’s assessment that the $441.50 quoted for the crack in the front bumper frame pad was warranted. This is despite the fact that the SJE was more than willing to make appropriate adjustments to the recommendations made in his report when confronted with the relevant evidence. 17     It is “axiomatic … that a judge is not entitled to substitute his own views for those of an uncontradicted expert’s” (_Sakthivel Punithavathi v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 2 SLR(R) 983</span> at \[76\]). Given the SJE’s unchallenged evidence that the front bumper frame pad was cracked due to the accident, $441.50 is awarded for this head of claim.

### Front headlight

18     I move to the front headlight. The Defendant submits that the photographs do not disclose any damage to the front headlight, and they could have been misleading as there was no breakage at all.

19     On cross-examination, Mr Tang agreed that the photographs did not disclose any damage to the headlight,[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19) although Mr Tang then proceeded to circle a photograph of the headlight to support his assertion that the headlight was cracked.[^20] The SJE circled the same part of the photograph:

![](data:image;base64,)

20     According to the SJE, any crack to even a minute plastic part of the headlight would require the entire headlight to be replaced due to “manufacturer spec\[ifications\]”.[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21) This is because even a small crack would cause water vapour and moisture in the glass.[^22]

21     However, the SJE agreed that since the headlight had to be dismantled along with the front bumper, there was a “risk that a worker who \[took\] out the bumper could break the particular part \[of the headlight\]” circled by the SJE.[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23) The SJE further accepted that the headlight did not appear to be cracked at the exterior,[^24] and he stated that he was unable to ascertain the actual cause of the alleged crack to the headlight:[^25]

> 
| 

Ct:

 | 

Given the force inflicted to the bumper in this case, is it likelier that the damage to the headlight was caused by the bumper stretching, or by manual extraction of the bumper and the headlight during the repair process?

 |
| 

E:

 | 

It happens to both.

 |
| 

Ct:

 | 

So you are unable to ascertain?

 |
| 

E:

 | 

Yes correct.

 |

  
  

22     Having considered the totality of evidence, I find that the alleged damage to the headlight was not caused by the accident. First, the photographs taken immediately after the accident do not show any scratches or damage to the headlight:[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26)

![](data:image;base64,)

23     Also, per the SJE’s evidence, any crack would likely have caused moisturisation within the glass of the headlight. Yet, no moisture can be seen in any of the photographs in the Surveyor’s report done in October 2018, about two months after the accident.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27) Also, neither the Plaintiff nor Mr Tang, who gave evidence for the Repairer, raised the issue of moisture in the headlight. Given this, even if I were inclined to accept that the headlight was damaged, I find on balance that such damage was not caused by the Defendant’s negligence, but rather by some source other than the accident, such as during the repair process. Accordingly, this head of claim is dismissed.

### Front sport wheel and front lower arm

24     For completeness, the claims for the front sport wheel and front lower arm are also dismissed. While the SJE had initially accepted these heads of claim, he revised his opinion on the stand, and stated unequivocally that these heads of claim were _not_ caused by the accident.[\[note: 28\]](#Ftn_28) This change in position is wholly consistent with the photographs of the accident; as the SJE explained during re-examination:[^29]

> 
| 

PC:

 | 

Is it also possible that there was a contact between the Defendant’s vehicle and the Plaintiff’s rim?

 |
| 

E:

 | 

During my initial assessment, it was based on the benefit of the doubt that the Plaintiff’s wheel was sticking out. Therefore the point of contact to the wheels and the lower arm are consistent. However, looking at exhibit photographs at DBOD 36-38 where the _Plaintiff’s car wheels are straight, then there is no way for a reversing car to come into contact with the wheel. There is no way to hit the wheel. The only point of contact is the bumper, that’s all_.

 |
| 

\[emphasis added\]

 |

  
  

### Labour costs

25     In his report, the SJE recommended that the total cost of the parts to be replaced or repaired due to the accident was $7,519.59. For such repairs, the SJE recommended that the cost of labour would be $900. While the total cost of the parts allowed is only $2,783.05,[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30) the labour costs should not be proportionately adjusted downwards given that such labour costs were incurred for checking the front electrical wiring, removing and refixing the front undercarriage, checking the wheel alignment, respraying and painting the car, and for removing and replacing the above parts. Regardless of the extent of damage, much of such costs would have had to be incurred during the repairing process that was necessitated by the Defendant’s negligence.

26     However, $150 is deducted from the $900 as some of the removal and replacement of parts (in particular the work done for the replacement of the front sport wheel and front lower arm) were unnecessary or did not flow from the accident (see \[23\] above). Accordingly, the cost of labour is fixed at $750.

### Total cost of repair

27     In total, the cost of repair is assessed at $3,533.05.[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31) However, applying the 20% lump-sum discount adopted by the SJE and the Plaintiff,[^32] such repair costs is scaled down to $2,826.44 + 7% GST, totalling $3,024.29.

## Cost of rental

28     As regards the cost of rental, Mr Tang Kok Wee Allan (“Mr Allan”), who gave evidence for the Car Rental Company, asserted that the replacement car provided to the Plaintiff was a BMW. However, apart from an invoice by the Car Rental Company,[\[note: 33\]](#Ftn_33) he could not provide any other evidence to show that a BMW had been rented to the Plaintiff.[^34]

29     Against Mr Allan’s self-serving evidence, the Plaintiff, who was the recipient of the car, testified that the car that was rented to her was an “old car” of Japanese make with a “used key”.[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35) Furthermore, the Plaintiff stated that as she had handed “everything to \[the Repairer\]”, she did not receive any invoice from the Car Rental Company as regards the car rental.[^36] It should also be observed that the Plaintiff’s signature in her affidavit of evidence-in-chief is strikingly different from the signature of the “renter” in the Car Rental Company’s invoice.[^37]

30     As such, the invoice from the Car Rental Company, which states that the car rented to the Plaintiff was a “BMW”, is of little corroborative value. Given that the Plaintiff had no reason to lie about the car that she received, I find that the car rented to the Plaintiff was _not_ a BMW, but rather one of Japanese make. Nonetheless, I accept that the car was rented to the Plaintiff for 7 days (from 1 to 8 October 2018)[\[note: 38\]](#Ftn_38) as the Plaintiff, who was upfront about the make of the car that she received, stated that she had received the replacement car for “about a week”.[^39] This is consistent with the Surveyor’s report, where it is stated that the first survey was done on 2 October 2018, and that the post-repair survey was done on 8 October 2018.[^40]

31     Here, I do not accept the Defendant’s submission that the number of days compensable to the Plaintiff for her rental costs should be reduced. Such rental costs were necessitated because the Plaintiff had to send her car for repair, and while some heads of claim were disallowed, there is nothing to suggest that the period of repair and surveying would have been reduced if these heads of claim were removed from the equation. For example, the headlights (which were not allowed) would have had to be dismantled with the front bumper in any event. No authorities have been cited by the Defendant for the proposition that the number of days of rental should be reduced (whether proportionately or otherwise) once the costs of repair awarded is reduced.

32     Thus, applying the benchmark rates for Category A vehicles in Appendix F of the State Courts Practice Directions, costs of rental is fixed at $100 x 7 = $700. In my view, the lowest end of the scale (of $100–$120) is warranted as the vehicle rented was, in the Plaintiff’s evidence, an old one.

33     No additional provision is made for the pre-repair survey report as the surveys were conducted on 2, 4 and 8 October 2018. These dates were covered by the rental period (from 1 to 8 October 2018), and the Plaintiff should not be compensated for the costs of rental _and_ for her loss of use for the same period as this would amount to double compensation.

## Conclusion

34     In total, damages is assessed at $3,724.29,[\[note: 41\]](#Ftn_41) to be paid by the Defendant to the Plaintiff. No pre-judgment interest is awarded on this sum as the Plaintiff does not appear to have paid any of the repair or rental charges to date, nor do any of the invoices addressed to her appear to require the payment of interest upon judgment. As such, in “both practical and equal terms\[,\] the financial position of the \[Plaintiff\] was wholly unaffected by the \[D\]efendant’s failure to make immediate payment”, and in “reality she was not ‘kept out of’ any money of her own whilst the claim was being assessed and litigated” (_Giles v Thompson_ <span class="citation">\[1993\] 2 WLR 908</span> at 925; see also _Tay Ken-Yang (Zheng Jingyang) v Siow Choon Meng_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGDC 201</span> at \[41\]–\[49\] and _Koh Tiam Ting v Soon Li Heng Civil Engineering Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGDC 172</span> at \[31\]–\[45\]).

35     I will hear parties on costs on a separate date.
